[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 13/100 path 2/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 13/100 path 2/5 answer="Let's denote:\n- \\( R \\) as the cost of each red car,\n- \\( A \\) as the cost of each action figure,\n- \\( D \\) as the cost of the doll.\n\nFrom the problem statement, we know:\n1. \\( R = \\$4 \\),\n2. \\( D = 3A + R \\),\n3. We need to find the total value of all toys.\n\nFirstly, let's calculate the total cost of the red cars and dolls based on their quantities and individual prices:\n\\[\n\\text{Total cost of red cars} = 5R = 5 \\times 4 = \\$20,\n\\]\n\\[\n\\text{Total cost of dolls} = D = 3A + 4.\n\\]\n\nNow, let's find out the cost of the action figures and the doll together using the given information:\n\\[\nD = 3A + R.\n\\]\n\nSubstituting \\( R = 4 \\):\n\\[\nD = 3A + 4.\n\\]\n\nWe also know that the total cost of all toys should equal $100 (since the wallet costs $100). Therefore:\n\\[\n(5R) + (3A + D) + D = 100.\n\\]\n\nPlugging in the values we already have:\n\\[\n20 + (3A + 4) + (3A + 4) = 100.\n\\]\n\nSimplify the equation:\n\\[\n20 + 4 + 4 + 6A = 100,\n\\]\n\\[\n28 + 6A = 100,\n\\]\n\\[\n6A = 100 - 28,\n\\]\n\\[\n6A = 72,\n\\]\n\\[\nA = \\frac{72}{6},"
