[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 15/100 path 4/5 answer="Let's denote the cost of one ticket to the fair as \\( T \\). According to the problem, three friends spent $20.25 on 3 tickets, so we can write:\n\n\\[ 3T = 20.25 \\]\n\nFrom this equation, we can solve for \\( T \\):\n\n\\[ T = \\frac{20.25}{3} \\]\n\\[ T = 6.75 \\]\n\nNext, let's determine the total amount spent on food. The problem states that they spent $4.50 less on food than on tickets, so the cost of food is:\n\n\\[ \\text{Cost of food} = 20.25 - 4.50 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Cost of food} = 15.75 \\]\n\nNow, let's calculate the total cost of the rides. Since they went on 2 different rides costing $33 each, the total cost for the rides is:\n\n\\[ \\text{Total cost of rides} = 2 \\times 33 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Total cost of rides} = 66 \\]\n\nAdding up all these expenses gives us the total cost:\n\n\\[ \\text{Total cost} = \\text{Cost of tickets} + \\text{Cost of food} + \\text{Total cost of rides} \\]\n\\[ \\text{Total cost} = 20.25 + 15.75 + 66 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Total cost} = 102 \\]\n\nFinally, since they agreed to split all these costs evenly among themselves, each person would have to pay:\n\n\\[ \\text{Amount each pays} = \\frac{\\text{Total cost}}{3} \\]\n\\[ \\text{Amount each pays} = \\frac{102}{3} \\"
