[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 78/100 path 1/3 answer="Let \\( S \\) represent the number of small stuffed animals sold, and let \\( L \\) represent the number of large stuffed animals sold. We know:\n\n\\[ S + L = 2L \\] (since Teresa sold twice as many small stuffed animals as large ones)\n\n\\[ 4S + 3(4L) = 120 \\] (since each small stuffed animal costs $4 and each large stuffed animal costs three times that amount)\n\nWe can simplify the second equation:\n\n\\[ 4S + 12L = 120 \\]\n\nNow we have two equations:\n\n1. \\( S + L = 2L \\)\n2. \\( 4S + 12L = 120 \\)\n\nFrom the first equation, we get:\n\n\\[ S = L \\]\n\nSubstitute \\( S = L \\) into the second equation:\n\n\\[ 4L + 12L = 120 \\]\n\\[ 16L = 120 \\]\n\\[ L = 7.5 \\]\n\nSince the number of stuffed animals sold cannot be a fraction, there seems to be an error in our calculations or assumptions. Let's re-evaluate the problem carefully.\n\nGiven:\n- Small stuffed animal cost = $4\n- Large stuffed animal cost = 3 * $4 = $12\n\nTeresa sold twice as many small stuffed animals as large ones, so if \\( L \\) is the number of large stuffed animals sold, then \\( 2L \\) is the number of small stuffed animals sold.\n\nTotal earnings from both types of stuffed animals should equal $120:\n\n\\[ 4S + 12L = 120 \\]\n\nWhere \\( S = 2L \\):\n\n\\[ 4(2L) + 12L = 120 \\]\n\\[ 8L"
