[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 82/100 path 1/3 answer='Let \\( J \\) represent the total number of jellyfish in the tank. According to the problem:\n\n1. One-fifth of the jellyfish are large:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{J}{5}\n   \\]\n\n2. Three-tenths (or one-third) of these large jellyfish change color:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{1}{3} \\times \\frac{J}{5} = \\frac{J}{15}\n   \\]\n\n3. The rest of the jellyfish remain small and do not change color:\n   \\[\n   J - \\frac{J}{5} = \\frac{4J}{5}\n   \\]\n\n4. We know that 6 jellyfish changed color:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{J}{15} + 6 = J\n   \\]\n\nNow solve for \\( J \\):\n\n\\[\n\\frac{J}{15} + 6 = J \\\\\n6 = J - \\frac{J}{15} \\\\\n6 = \\frac{15J - J}{15} \\\\\n6 = \\frac{14J}{15} \\\\\n90 = 14J \\\\\nJ = \\frac{90}{14} \\\\\nJ = 6.42857...\n\\]\n\nSince the number of jellyfish must be a whole number, we round down to the nearest whole number:\n\n\\[\nJ = 6\n\\]\n\nHowever, there seems to be a discrepancy because our calculation suggests less than 6 jellyfish. Let’s recheck the logic:\n\nIf 6 jellyfish changed color, they were all either large or small. Since large jellyfish account for \\(\\frac{J}{5}\\), let’s assume \\(L\\) is the number of large jellyfish:\n\n\\[\nL = \\frac{J}{5}\n\\]\n\nAnd'
